Because not all paint is created equal (or equally shiny).
So, you’re staring at a wall, a paint swatch in one hand, a half-used coffee in the other, and you’re thinking: “Why are there so many dang finishes?” Matte, eggshell, satin, gloss… What do they all mean? Do they actually make a difference, or is it just a way for paint companies to mess with us?
Breathe easy. I’m breaking down the most common paint sheens so you don’t have to Google “What the heck is eggshell paint?” ever again.
1. Matte (a.k.a. Flat)
Vibe: Soft, smooth, zero shine.Best for: Bedrooms, ceilings, low-traffic areas.
Matte paint is basically the introvert of the paint world. It doesn’t try to shine or stand out. It just quietly does its job—giving you rich color and hiding imperfections like a pro. Got bumpy walls or patchy drywall? Matte’s your BFF. But here’s the catch: it’s not great with cleaning. If your kid decides the wall is their next canvas, you’ll need more than a magic eraser.
In short: Great for a cozy, modern vibe, but not ideal if your walls get a lot of action.
2. Eggshell
Vibe: Just a hint of sheen—think of the soft glow of, well, an eggshell.Best for: Living rooms, dining rooms, hallways.
Eggshell is the middle ground between matte and satin. It’s got that barely-there glow that makes walls look alive without screaming, “Look at me!” Plus, it’s easier to clean than matte, making it a solid choice for spots where people gather—but maybe not where they wrestle.
In short: A safe, stylish go-to for most rooms. Not too shiny, not too flat. Goldilocks would approve.
3. Satin
Vibe: Silky smooth with a soft glow.Best for: Kitchens, bathrooms, kids’ rooms, high-traffic areas.
Satin is like the overachiever of paint sheens. It’s got durability, it’s easy to wipe down, and it looks polished without being blinding. It’s perfect if your walls are going to be touched, splashed, or otherwise abused on a regular basis. The only downside? It shows wall imperfections more than matte or eggshell, so prep work matters.
In short: Shiny enough to clean, but not so shiny you feel like you’re in a funhouse mirror.
4. Gloss (and Semi-Gloss)
Vibe: Shiny and reflective—like lip gloss for your walls.Best for: Trim, doors, cabinets, bathrooms.
Gloss and semi-gloss are where things start getting fancy (and a little dramatic). These finishes bounce light around like nobody’s business, so they’re great for small spaces that need a little extra brightness. They’re also super wipeable, making them ideal for spots that get grubby (hello, baseboards). Just know that gloss will show off every imperfection, like the wall equivalent of high-def TV.
In short: Great for accents and places that need serious cleaning power, but not for hiding flaws.
Final Thoughts: What Should You Pick?
Think of sheen like personality.
Want cozy and moody? Go matte.
Prefer something classic and clean? Eggshell.
Need something that can handle chaos? Satin.
Want to make trim or doors pop? Gloss or semi-gloss.
And remember: you don’t have to stick to one sheen for your whole house. Mix it up! Matte in the bedroom, satin in the kitchen, gloss on the trim—it’s all about matching the right finish to the right job.
Happy painting—and may your walls be ever in your favor.

